last_replies.name: Anonymous
last_replies.com:
>>26087974
you have to get the engine up to operating temp then let one of the vacuum lines on the intake manifold suck the liquid out of the can, or you can pour it into an open hose.
after you've done about half a can turn the car off and let it sit, 10 minutes minimum but an hour or so is best. 6h-overnight is a little too long, the seafoam will evaporate and the engine will cool.
when you start the car up there will be a ton of white smoke and it may run rough, you should go drive the car hard and rev it up high, which will clear out the loosened soot. you should notice an immediate difference in the way the engine responds and sounds after all the smoke stops.
if the car doesn't generally run better afterwards do it again -- make sure you hooked the vacuum line back up too.
if you successfully cleaned out its sinuses with only half the can pour the rest of the seafoam into the gas tank, it works similarly to techron and v-power, will keep your fuel system clean and help reduce future deposits.
do not pour it into oil that you are planning on driving on, it will thin it out. probably a good idea to change the oil after a top end cleaning too.

you can avoid having to use seafoam by installing a catch can instead of letting the pcv system shit in your intake, using premium fuels that already come with some of seafoam's detergents, and maintaining your air filter.
